Jesus went from there. He walked beside the Sea of Galilee. He went up on a mountain and sat down.
He had great multitudes come to him, bringing him blind people and those who could not walk. They brought him cripples, people who could not speak, and many others. They placed them before him, and he healed them.
The people were amazed. Those who could not speak began to speak. The disabled were healed. Those who could not walk began to walk. Those who were blind began to see. And the people praised the God of Israel.
Then Jesus called his disciples to him and said, "I have compassion on these people; they have been with me for three days and have nothing to eat. I do not want to send them away hungry, or they may collapse on the way."
His disciples answered him, "Where could we get enough bread in this desolate place to feed such a crowd?"
"How many loaves do you have?" asked Jesus. "Seven," they answered, "and some small fish."
Jesus told the crowd to sit down on the ground.
He took the seven loaves and the fish, and having given thanks, he broke them and gave them to the disciples. And the disciples gave them to the people.
They all ate and were satisfied. And the disciples picked up seven baskets of the broken pieces that were left over.
The number of men who ate was 4000. Women and children also ate.
After Jesus had dismissed the crowds, he got into the boat and went to the region of Magadan.
Jesus was asked to perform a miracle as proof.
The Pharisees and Sadducees came to test Jesus, and they asked him to show them a sign from heaven to prove his miraculous power.
He replied, "In the evening you look at the sky. You say, 'The weather will be good. The sky is red.'"
And when you see the morning, you say: "Today there will be a storm, the sky is red and overcast." You know the meaning of what you see in the sky. But you cannot understand the signs of what is happening now.
"An evil and adulterous generation seeks after a sign! And no sign will be given to it except the sign of Jonah." And He left them and went away. The leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees
The students walked to the other side of the lake. They forgot to bring bread.
Jesus said to them, "Beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees."
The pupils spoke about this among themselves, saying, "He must have said this because we did not bring bread with us."
Jesus knew what they were saying, and he said to them, "Your faith is very small. Why are you talking to each other about having no bread?"
Don't you understand yet? Don't you think about those five loaves that fed five thousand? Don't you remember the number of baskets you filled with the pieces?
Don't you remember the seven loaves of the four thousand? Don't you remember how many baskets full of pieces you gathered?
How can you not understand? I was not talking to you about bread. But beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees.
And then the disciples understood that Jesus was not asking them to beware of the leaven used in bread, but was warning them about what the Pharisees and Sadducees were teaching. Peter says that Jesus is the Christ.
Jesus went to the region of Caesarea Philippi. He asked his disciples, "Who do people say the Son of Man is?"
They answered, "Some say John the Baptist, others say Elijah, and still others Jeremiah or one of the prophets."
"But what about you?" he asked. "Who do you say that I am?"
Simon Peter answered, "You are the Christ, the Son of the living God."
Jesus answered, "Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah! For flesh and blood has not revealed this to you, but my Father who is in heaven."
This is what I tell you: You are Peter, and on this rock I will build my church. And the gates of hell will not be strong enough to destroy it.
I will give you the keys to the kingdom of heaven. Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you loose on earth will be loosed in heaven.
And Jesus warned his disciples that they should tell no one that he was the Christ. Jesus spoke of his coming death.
From that time on, Jesus began to explain to his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem and suffer many things at the hands of the elders, chief priests, and teachers of the law. He must be killed, and on the third day be raised to life.
Peter took Jesus aside and began to rebuke him. "Never, Lord!" he said. "This shall never happen to you!"
Jesus turned and said to Peter, "Get behind me, Satan! You are a stumbling block to me; you do not have in mind the concerns of God, but merely human concerns."
Then Jesus said to his disciples, "If anyone would come after me, he must deny himself and take up his cross and follow me.
If he wants to save his life, he will lose it. But if he loses his life for my sake, he will find it.
"What good is it for a person to gain the whole world, yet forfeit their soul? Or what can a person give in exchange for their soul?"
"The son of man will come in the glory of his Father, and with him will be his angels. And then he will reward each according to what they have done."
What I am about to tell you is true. Some of the people standing here will not die before they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom.
Jesus' features changed as he appeared.
Six days later, Jesus took with him Peter and James and John, the brother of James, and led them up a high mountain by themselves.
And there before them his appearance was altered. His face shone like the sun, and his clothes became as white as light.
Then Moses and Elijah appeared to them, talking with Jesus.
Peter said to Jesus, "Lord, it is good that we are here. If you wish, I will make three booths. One for you, one for Moses, and one for Elijah."
And while Peter was still speaking, a bright cloud enveloped them. A voice from the cloud said, "This is my Son, whom I love. I am very pleased with him. Listen to him!"
When the students heard this, they were very afraid. They fell to the ground on their faces.
But Jesus came and touched them, saying, "Arise, do not be afraid."
And when they lifted up their eyes, they saw no one but Jesus.
They came down from the mountain. And as they were coming down, Jesus commanded them, saying, "Tell no one what you have seen. Wait until the Son of Man has risen from the dead."
The disciples asked him, "Why then do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?"
Jesus answered, "That is true. Elijah is supposed to come and make everything new again.
But I tell you, Elijah has come, and they did not recognize him, but treated him however they pleased. So also will the Son of Man suffer at their hands.
The disciples began to understand that Jesus was speaking to them about John the Baptist. Jesus healed a boy who had a demon.
And when they came near to the multitude, a man knelt down before Jesus.
He said, "O Lord, have mercy on my son, for he trembles greatly and suffers much. He often falls into the fire or into the water."
I brought him to your disciples, but they could not heal him.
Then Jesus answered and said, "O faithless and perverse generation! How long shall I be with you? How long shall I bear with you? Bring the boy here to me."
Jesus commanded the demon to come out of the boy, and it did. He was healed instantly.
And afterward Jesus' disciples came to him in the fields, and said to him, "Why could we not cast it out?"
He replied, "Because your faith is very weak. What I am about to tell you is the truth. If you have faith as small as a mustard seed, it is enough. You can say to this mountain, 'Move from here to there,' and it will move. Nothing will be impossible for you."
